      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <p><lb n="1"/><supplied cert="low" reason="lost">siddhaM| catur-udadhi-salilāsvāditayaśaso mahārājādhirāja-śrī-kumāraguptasya</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">sa</supplied>mvatsara-śa<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->te</supplied> trayodaśotta<!--
I adopt Sircar's conjecture for the beginning except hypothesising siddham instead of his oṁ.
--><lb break="no" n="2"/><supplied reason="lost">re</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="23" reason="lost" unit="character"/><!--
Sircar's conjecture for the beginning of this line is saṁ 100+10+3 (after re, I guess, though he may have read re at the end of the first line - which I consider very unlikely)
--></p>
        <p><supplied reason="lost">asyā</supplied><sic>n</sic> d<unclear>i</unclear>vasa-pūrvvāyāṁ parama-daivata-para<lb break="no" n="3"/><supplied reason="lost">ma-bhaṭṭāraka-</supplied><supplied cert="low" reason="lost">mahārājādhirāja-śrī-kumāragupte pr̥thivīpatau</supplied> kuṭu<unclear>mbi</unclear> <gap precision="low" quantity="3" reason="lost" unit="character"/> brāhmaṇa-śivaśarmma-nāgaśarmma-maha<!--
The conjectural filling-up is from Lielukhine, i.e. probably Sircar. Compare the Damodarpur plates. Bhandarkar reads ā(?) before kuṭumbi, I see nothing (not even kuṭumbi), but this could be part of an au mātrā. The broken-off gap after kuṭumbi is 2 or 3 characters in size, but I can't make out brāhmaṇa either on the facsimile, nor anything else really, except what may be śi of śivaśarmma.
--><lb break="no" n="4"/><gap precision="low" quantity="19" reason="lost" unit="character"/>vakīrtti-kṣemadatta-goṣṭhaka-varggapāla-piṅgala-śuṅkuka-kāla<!--
Lielukhine (naming no source) proposes Śivakīrtti for the partially lost name and says Banerji reads kṣamavanta, presumably for kṣemadatta.
--><lb break="no" n="5"/><gap precision="low" quantity="20" reason="lost" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">pa</unclear>viṣṇu-<unclear>deva</unclear>śarmma-viṣṇubhadra-khāsaka-rāmaka-gopāla<!--
Lielukhine says Banerji reads viṣyabhadra instead of viṣṇubhadra.
--><lb n="6"/><gap precision="low" quantity="18" reason="lost" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">sasu</unclear> śrībhadra-somapāla-rāmā<unclear cert="low">dyāḥ</unclear> grāmāṣṭa-kulādhikaraṇañ ca<!--
Bhandarkar reads Rām-ādyāḥ(?); no way to tell if the question mark is meant just for the visarga or for more. Lielukhine (Sircar?) has rāmādyaka, also with a question mark.
--><!--
Lielukhine also has °karaṇaśca at the end.
--><!--
And while we're at it, Bhandarkar's sa(?) su(?) may represent two alternatives rather than two successive characters? I can't make out anything on the photo.
--><lb break="no" n="7"/><gap precision="low" quantity="15" reason="lost" unit="character"/>viṣṇu<unclear cert="low">nā</unclear> vijñāpitā Iha khādā<unclear cert="low">ṭa</unclear>pāra-viṣaye nuvr̥tta-maryyādā-sthi<unclear>ti</unclear><!--
again, the ? after viṣṇunā may refer to more than just the nā. Lielukhine also has ṇā in brackets with a question mark, probably meaning that the original text may have ṇā.
--><!--
Lielukhine says Banerji read mahākhuṣāpāra instead of khādā(?ṭa)pāra.
--><lb n="8"/><gap precision="low" quantity="15" reason="lost" unit="character"/>nīvī-dharmma-kṣayeṇa labhya<unclear>te</unclear><!--
Sircar reads nīvīdharmmākṣayeṇa rather than kṣayeṇa; Bhandarkar mentions his interpretation of kṣaya in his introduction of this inscr.
--></p>
        <p><unclear>ta</unclear>d arhatha mamādyānenaiva kkrame<choice>
            <sic>n</sic>
            <corr>ṇ</corr>
          </choice>a dā<unclear>tuṁ</unclear>
<lb n="9"/><gap precision="low" quantity="14" reason="lost" unit="character"/>samety<unclear cert="low">ā</unclear>bhihitai<unclear cert="low">ḥ</unclear> sarvvam eva <unclear cert="low">jñā</unclear>kara-prative<unclear cert="low">śi</unclear>-kuṭumbibhir avasthāpya ka<!--
Sircar restores Bhandarkar's (jñā?)kara as kṣetrakara.
--><lb break="no" n="10"/><gap precision="low" quantity="14" reason="lost" unit="character"/>ri <gap precision="low" quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> kana <gap precision="low" quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> yad ito <gap precision="low" quantity="2" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear>ta</unclear>d avadhr̥tam iti yatas tatheti pratipādya
<lb n="11"/><gap precision="low" quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost">aṣṭaka-na</supplied>vaka-nalā<unclear>bhyā</unclear>m apaviñchya kṣetra-kulya-vāpam ekaṁ dattaṁ tataḥ Āyuktaka-
<lb n="12"/><gap precision="low" quantity="14" reason="lost" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">bhrā</unclear>tr̥-kaṭaka-vāstavya-chandoga-brāhmaṇa-varāhasvāmino dattaṁ taddha<unclear cert="low">va</unclear><lb break="no" n="13"/><gap precision="low" quantity="16" reason="lost" unit="character"/>bhūmyā dā<unclear>nākṣe</unclear>pe ca guṇāguṇam anucintya śarīra-k<unclear>ā</unclear>ñcanakasya ci<lb break="no" n="14"/><supplied reason="lost">ra-cañcalatvaṁ</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="10" reason="lost" unit="character"/> <seg subtype="consonant" type="component">
            <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
          </seg>ā<!--
the conjecture ra-cañcalatvaṁ is present in Sircar (probably his own?) and Agrawala, but not mentioned at all in Bhandarkar.
--><!--
ā after the lacuna is only found in Bhandarkar. I assume he saw a diacritical ā, not a full vowel.
--></p>
        <p><unclear>u</unclear>ktañ ca bhagavatā dvaipāyanena
</p>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="1">
          <l n="a">svadattām para-dattām vā</l>
          <l n="b">
            <lb n="15"/>
            <supplied reason="lost">yo hareta vasundharām</supplied>
          </l>
          <l n="c">
            <supplied reason="lost">sa viṣṭhāyāṁ kr̥mir bhūtvā</supplied>
          </l>
          <l n="d"><supplied reason="lost">pitr̥</supplied><unclear>bhiḥ</unclear> saha pacyate</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="2">
          <l n="a">ṣaṣṭiṁ varṣa-sahasrā<choice>
              <sic>n</sic>
              <corr>ṇ</corr>
            </choice>i</l>
          <l n="b">svargge modati <unclear>bhū</unclear>midaḥ</l>
          <l n="c">
            <lb n="16"/>
            <supplied reason="lost">Ākṣeptā cānumantā ca</supplied>
          </l>
          <l n="d">
            <supplied reason="lost">tāny eva narake vaset</supplied>
          </l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="3">
          <l n="a"><unclear>pū</unclear>rvva-dattāṁ dvijātibhyo</l>
          <l n="b">yatnād rakṣa yudhiṣṭhira</l>
          <l n="c">mahīṁ <unclear>mahī</unclear><supplied reason="lost">matāñ cchreṣṭha</supplied></l>
          <l n="d">
            <lb n="17"/>
            <supplied reason="lost">dānāc chreyo nupālanam</supplied>
          </l>
        </lg>
        <p><gap precision="low" quantity="10" reason="lost" unit="character"/>ya<unclear>ṁ</unclear> <unclear cert="low">su</unclear>śrībhadrena Utkīrṇṇaṁ sthambheśvaradāse<unclear>na</unclear> <gap precision="low" quantity="5" reason="lost" unit="character"/><!--
Sircar restores the lacuna as likhitā paṭṭikeyaṁ amātyabhadreṇa (Bhadra as the name, not preceding the other -bhadra). He also says traces of ka are visible before ya(ṁ). Bhandarkar follows Basak in reading suśrībhadreṇa.
--><!--
Bhandarkar corrects the other name to stambheśvara-; Sircar reports Banerji as reading sthahṇeśvara (while Lielukhine reports Basak as reading so); Agrawala reads or conjectures Sthāṇvīśvara.
--><!--
note that the final 5 lost characters are only there if the line extends to the edge of the plate, but there isn't really anything else expected here
--></p>
